You are converting a finished ideation branch into a set of GitHub issues. Read the
node artifacts in this directory (Read tool) to ground yourself in the actual thinking,
then produce a JSON object describing one epic issue and its child implementation issues.

## The session seed (operator input, trusted)
<%= @seed_prompt %>

## The branch root to promote
Title: <%= @idea_title %>
Summary: <%= @idea_summary %>
Score: <%= @idea_score %> · Depth: <%= @idea_depth %>

## Ancestor chain (root → branch root)
<%= @ancestor_chain %>

## Subtree (branch root + all descendants)
<%= @subtree %>

## Journal excerpt
<%= @journal %>

## Your task

Read the artifact files listed above (node-N.md) for the nodes in this subtree to
understand the full thinking. Then produce a JSON object with:

- `epic` — A tracking issue tying the work together.
  - `title`: one crisp line, e.g. "Implement X for Y" (≤ 72 chars).
  - `body`: motivation paragraph, proposed approach, acceptance criteria, non-goals.

- `children` — 2–8 concrete implementation issues, each independently actionable.
  Each child must:
  - Be **xs or s scope** — one focused, locatable change per issue.
  - Include **specific code references** (file paths, function/module names) so a
    reader does not need to re-derive the location.
  - Include **acceptance criteria** — what does done look like? what test proves it?
  - Include **explicit non-goals** — what is deliberately out of scope for this issue?
  - Have a **one crisp change** — if two concerns appear, split them.
  - Be written so the triage stage would confidently label it `auto` or `plan`:
    well-specified, risk flags stated, no ambiguity about what changes.

Write the body of each child in GitHub Markdown. Do not include the parent epic link
in the body — the harness adds it automatically. Do not invent code paths; if you are
not certain a file or function exists, say "needs investigation" in the acceptance
criteria.

Your final response must be only the JSON object matching the provided schema.
